We have that $(7+2i)^{90} = (1+i)^{90}$ using De Moivre's Theorem.  We can write $(1+i)$ as $\sqrt{2}\left(\cos\frac{\pi}{4}+\sin\frac{\pi}{4}i\right)$.  This means that \begin{align*}
(1+i)^{90}&=\left(\sqrt{2}\left(\cos\frac{\pi}{4}+\sin\frac{\pi}{4}i\right)\right)^{90}\\
&=2^{45/2}\left(\cos\frac{3\pi}{4}+\sin\frac{3\pi}{4}i\right)\\
&=\boxed{-\frac{1}{2}-\frac{i}{2}}.
\end{align*} #### -\frac{1}{2}-\frac{i}{2}

