Since $f(x)$ is an odd function, we have that $f(-x) = -f(x)$.  Since $g(x)$ is an even function, we have that $g(-x) = g(x)$.  Then $f(g(-x)) = f(g(x))$, so $f(g(f(g(f(x)))))) = f(g(f(g(x)))$.

If we apply $f$ to both sides, we get $$f(f(g(f(g(f(x)))))) = f(g(f(g(x))) \quad\text{and} \quad f(g(f(g(f(x)))))) = f(g(f(g(x))).$$

Therefore, $f(f(g(f(g(f(x)))))) = f(g(f(g(x)))$, which means that this expression is even.  So the answer is $\boxed{\text{even}}$. #### \text{even}

